INSERT IGNORE INTO `wp_f0npwq3mss_posts` VALUES (714, 1, '2016-07-03 23:20:40', '2016-07-03 23:20:40', 'When we started our first automation testing project using Cucumber with Selenium in the year 2012, we thought that it is just an another automation framework and approach. But later we, at Codoid realized that we were going in the wrong direction.\r\n\r\nLessons are learnt and our test scripts are corrected within a week. The goal of this blog post is sharing Cucumber Best Practices which are ingredients for our successful Cucumber automation projects. Let’s see it one by one.\r\n\r\n<h3>Write readable steps</h3>\r\n\r\nNever ever write Gherkin steps as shown below:\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nScenario: User logs in\r\n\r\n  Given I am on the homepage\r\n\r\n  When I click on the "Login" button\r\n\r\n   And I enter "Email" textbox with "stewart@codoid.com"\r\n\r\n   And I enter "Password" textbox with "**********"\r\n\r\n   And I click on "Login"\r\n\r\n  Then I should see Welcome page\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nAfter reading this Gherkin, you may ask why it is not readable? \r\n\r\nThis is a very simple scenario, so you are able to understand with or without declarative statements. Consider, if you have a scenario with 10 \'I click\' and 20 \'I enter\' statements, then you will not be able to explain what the scenario does without reading the title. It is very hard to follow a scenario with imperative style, difficult to maintain and not helpful for stakeholders.\r\n\r\nNext problem, if there is a functionality or UI change, then updating steps is not an easy job. Let\'s take an example.\r\n\r\n<pre class="brush:plain">\r\nFeature: Ticket booking\r\n\r\nBackground: User login\r\n\r\nGiven I am on the home page\r\nWhen I enter "Email" textbox with "mark@codoid.com"\r\n And I enter "Password" textbox with "*******"\r\n And I click Login button\r\nThen I should see Welcome page\r\n\r\nScenario: Book a one way ticket\r\n\r\nGiven I click \'Book a ticket\' button\r\n And I am on Book Ticket page\r\nWhen I select "Washinton DC" in \'From\' combobox\r\n And I select "Chicago" in \'To\' combobox\r\n And I select date of Journey as \'07/24/2016\'\r\n And I click \'Book\' button\r\nThen I should see Payment page\r\n\r\nScenario: Book and Cancel a ticket\r\n\r\nGiven I click \'Book a ticket\' button\r\n And I am on Book Ticket page\r\n And I select "Washinton DC" in \'From\' combobox\r\n And I select "Chicago" in \'To\' combobox \r\n And I select date of Journey as \'07/24/2016\'\r\n And I click \'Book\' button\r\n And I should see Payment page\r\nWhen I click \'Cancel\' button\r\nThen I should see Ticket Cancelled page\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<strong>Problem</strong>\r\nIf a new step is introduced right after \'I select date of Journey\' for every new ticket booking, then you need to update both the scenarios\' gherkin and add new step definition.\r\n\r\n<strong>Solution:</strong>\r\nFollow Declarative Style\r\n<pre class="brush:plain">\r\nAnd I book a ticket from \'Washinton DC\' to \'Chicago\' with date of Journey as \'07/24/2016\'\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nIf your feature is written with declarative style, then you need to update only the existing step definition.\r\n\r\nNote: If you are compelled to make a change in feature file due to a functionality change even after following declarative style, don\'t worry now your gherkins are more readable, you can make the changes quickly and no need to go through several \'I click\', \'I enter\' & \'I press\' steps to understand the feature.\r\n\r\n<h3>Narrate Your Feature</h3>\r\nNarrative gives overview of your feature.\r\n<strong>Example </strong>\r\n<pre class="brush:plain">\r\nFeature: Class Management\r\nNarrative Description: As a Teacher, I want Class Management feature, so that I can a create class and assign students to classes\r\n</pre>\r\n<h3>Use Background for repeating Given steps</h3>\r\nIf the GIVEN steps are repeating in all the scenarios in a feature, then place them in Background.\r\n<h3>Write Independent Scenarios</h3>\r\nIt is very easy to trouble-shoot a failed independent scenario. Executing and fixing coupled scenarios is nightmare.   \r\n<h3>Group Scenarios using Tags</h3>\r\nThere is no standard industry best practice for Cucumber feature/scenario tagging, but the goal is you need to group your scenarios to ease script execution and testing.\r\n\r\n<strong>Examples:</strong>\r\n@smoke @regression - For Testing types\r\n@sikuli - To identify Sikuli scripts\r\n@module1 @module2 - To run module1 and module2 scenarios\r\n<h3>Keep it simple</h3>\r\n<img alt=\'cucumber best practices\' src=\'http://www.codoid.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Cucumber_Testing.png\'/>\r\nDon\'t try to introduce one more layer between step definition and page object.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'Cucumber Best Practices', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '701-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-07-03 23:20:40', '2016-07-03 23:20:40', '', 701, 'http://www.codoid.com/701-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
